If you are only able to view Bitcoin‚Äôs potential for success vis-a-vis the US Dollar, you‚Äôre really missing out on most of what bitcoin‚Äôs short-to-medium term potential actually is. 

Hate me if you want, but I think hyperbitcoinization is currently not in the cards. Never say never. But if that‚Äôs what you expect to happen in the coming months and years, I think you‚Äôre just completely wrong about that. 

At the same time, Bitcoin is going to keep growing and filling in gaps all around the world, where financial access is far more adversarial. It‚Äôs also going to revolutionize the reach of global payments, secure identities, and I believe things like Lightning are going to become ways to accept global payments from anywhere in the world for services, tips, and things like zaps! 

Many people will convert their payments back into local fiat. Some will save in bitcoin. That‚Äôs okay! Measuring Bitcoin‚Äôs success or failure in absolute terms just causes serious distraction from what the near-term opportunities are.

To truly understand the unique position #Bitcoin holds, one must view the situation not as a rivalry between competing projects, but as a grand re-imagination of the concept of money itself. Bitcoin, in this sense, becomes not a mere component in a crowded field, but the quintessential embodiment of the potential of decentralized money.

Bitcoin's ethos embodies the principles of transparency, immutability, and decentralization. It's a profound rebuke to the opaque, mutable, and centralized nature of traditional financial institutions. Bitcoin‚Äôs simplicity is its strength.

This fundamental focus gives Bitcoin an enduring resilience, even in the face of institutional regulatory threats, such as those posed by the likes of the SEC. While the SEC can scrutinize specific projects, introduce regulations, or even levy fines, the influence it can exert is somewhat limited to the jurisdiction it presides over.

But it's the ethos, the philosophical commitment to a certain vision of decentralized money that Bitcoin represents, that could pose a greater challenge to altcoins. It's not about superiority or imposition, but rather about drawing on the essence of what made Bitcoin a revolution in the first place.
